ery rare in France. Compare   Zeno  .","History: Jean Miel (or Amiel) <i>dit</i> Lusignan from Lusignan in Vienne, France, married Marie-Thérèse Latouche in Boucherville, QC, in 1699. — A French family called <i>(de) Lusignan</i> became enormously powerful in the eastern Mediterranean during the Middle Ages. Guy de Lusignan (1129–94) was king of Cyprus from 1192 to 1194 (and before that, by right of marriage, king of the crusader state of Jerusalem). Hugues de Lusignan was king of Cyprus from 1267 to 1284 and king of Jerusalem from 1268 to 1284. During the 14th century, Lusignans became kings of the Armenian kingdom of Cilicia (on the Mediterranean coast of what is now Turkey, facing Cyprus)."],"variants":[{"name":"Zeno","meanings":["Italian (mainly southern Italy), Hispanic (mainly Puerto Rico), and African American: from the personal name <i>Zeno</i>, classical Greek <i>Zēnōn</i>, a derivative of <i>Zeus</i>, the name of the king of the gods in Greek mythology. <i>Zeno</i> or <i>Zenone</i> is the name of a 4th-century Italian saint from Verona. As an African American name it was probably adopted in honor of the Stoic philosopher Zeno of Kition.","Altered form of French   Lusignan  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mahaut de LUSIGNAN was born about 1210, in France, her father, Raoul I of Lusignan, was 48 and her mother, Marguerite Sibylle de Courtenay, was 18. She had at least 1 daughter with Guillaume de Chauvigny."},"et":{"ABT 1210–":"umbes 1210–Surnud","1165–1241":"1165–1241","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1192–1234":"1192–1234","1230–1323":"1230–1323","1164–1219":"1164–1219","1194–1270":"1194–1270","1165":"1165","1164":"1164","1230":"1230","1241":"1241","1194":"1194","1270":"1270","1192":"1192","ABT 1230":"umbes 1230","1323":"1323","ABT 1210":"umbes 1210","1234":"1234","1210":"1210","1219":"1219","Europa":"Europe","-,,,,FRANCE,":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"ABT 1210–":"noin 1210–Kuollut","1165–1241":"1165–1241","1210–Female":"1210–Kuollut","1192–1234":"1192–1234","1230–1323":